[[Japan]] is the [[Global music industry market share data|second-largest music market in the world]] and the following lists cover the top-selling albums in the country of Japan, based on information provided by the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] and [[Oricon|Original Confidence Inc.]], commonly known as Oricon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riaj.or.jp/riaj/pdf/issue/industry/RIAJ2006E.pdf|title=RIAJ: Yearbook 2006, IFPI 2004 Report (Page 23)|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref>

==Best-selling physical albums in Japan==
In the history of the [[Oricon]] weekly albums chart, which started in January 1970, only 280 out of all of the charting albums have sold more than one million copies, a feat mostly achieved by domestic acts.<ref name="Japanese million albums">{{cite web | url=http://www.musictvprogram.com/corner-ranking-album.html | script-title=ja:歴代アルバムランキング TOP280 | author=オリジナルコンフィデンス | publisher=Music TV Program | accessdate=4 November 2017 | language=ja}}</ref>

===List of best-selling albums by domestic acts===
This is the list of the top-selling albums in Japan, based on data compiled by Oricon. Prior to January 1987, the domestic albums chart was separated into [[LP record|LPs]] (created in 1970), [[compact Cassette|cassette tapes]] (introduced in 1974) and [[CD|compact discs]] (launched in 1985), until their unification, which remains the current form. It is worth noting that Oricon only takes into consideration physical sales for its charts, meaning that digital purchases are excluded.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/tv/top40/ | title=動画:oricon TOP40-無料動画-ORICON STYLE | work=oricon.co.jp | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080126210639/http://www.oricon.co.jp/tv/top40/ | archivedate=January 26, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://nendai-ryuukou.com/article/014.html | script-title=ja:歴代CDアルバム売り上げ枚数ランキング | author=オリジナルコンフィデンス | publisher=年代流行 | accessdate=4 November 2017 | language=ja}}</ref><ref name="Japanese million albums"/> The best-selling album is ''[[First Love (Utada Hikaru album)|First Love]]'' by female solo artist [[Utada Hikaru]], sold in over 7.5 million copies by the end of 1999.<ref name="hmv_japan_top100">{{cite web|title=Top 100 Japanese pops Artists – No.30|work=[[HMV|HMV Japan]]|language=Japanese|url=http://www.hmv.co.jp/news/newsDetail.asp?newsnum=310190005|date=2003-11-01|accessdate=2013-01-15}}</ref> [[Ryuichi Kawamura]]'s album ''Love'' (1997) topped the album chart with sales of around 1,021,000 copies, making him the only male solo artist ever to have an album sell over one million copies within its initial week in Oricon charts history.<ref name="firstweek">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/3315/|script-title=ja:平井堅ベスト盤が首位！ 初動売上は男性ソロ史上3番目の大ヒット！|publisher=Oricon|date=2005-11-29|accessdate=2010-06-23|language=Japanese}}</ref> That same album sold over 2,788,000 copies, therefore it holds the record for best selling male solo album.<ref name="twomillion">{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/ranking/18171/|script-title=ja:平井堅、男性ソロ史上3人目の快挙！べスト盤が200万枚突破！|publisher=[[Oricon]]|date=2006-04-10|accessdate=2010-03-08|language=Japanese}}</ref>

